<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBAFFE06DC2FF46FE85AA29" pageId="30" pageNumber="1543" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBAFFE06DC2FF46FE85AA29" blockId="30.[178,1085,219,299]" pageId="30" pageNumber="1543">
Etymology: The trivial name 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBAFFE06F4DFF46FD40ABF2" box="[573,725,219,240]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1543">flavohumeralis</emphasis>
, is a Latin compound name that stems from 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBAFFE06C5BFF65FEF2AA0F" box="[299,359,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1543">flavus</emphasis>
(= yellow) and 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBAFFE06F7DFF65FDF1AA0F" box="[525,612,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="1543">humerus</emphasis>
(= shoulder). I refer to the color of the elytral humerus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
